<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-601-144  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 601 144.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  August 17 1989 v15 n17 p29(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mastering financial information - on-line: a look at howinformation managers can regain control in the financialcommunity.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yakimischak, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Service to the financial industry continues to be one of thedriving forces in the development of information and databasesystems and the hardware/software that accesses them.andP;  The tickerhas evolved into high-speed digital pipelines that deliverinformation to be filtered, processed, stored and retrieved.andP;  Inaddition to these numeric services there are text-based servicesoffering news, research and commentary.andP;  Vendors once suppliedproprietary machines and networks, organized as turnkey systems,to handle the unique needs of businesses for hardware, software,information and maintenance.andP;  The trend now is toward purchasingdigital information in bulk and manipulating it by means offinancial software on industry-standard microcomputers,workstations or local area networks.andP;  The challenge for thecommunications manager is to configure the most appropriate systemfor his company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information ServicesFinancial SoftwareFinancial ServicesTurnkey SystemsInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>